    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:aa6db507-4ec6-44b6-abb3-a07e156dbef4",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
          "status": "generated",
          "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\">patient-description</div>"
        },
        "category": [
          {
            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-description"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} is a 7-year-old boy who appears mildly unwell but not toxic. He is alert, interactive, and appropriately shy at first, staying close to his mother during the visit. He has a runny nose with frequent wiping, intermittent dry cough, watery eyes, and mild facial flushing. His voice is slightly hoarse, and he breathes comfortably at rest, though he occasionally sniffles and coughs during conversation. His clothing is clean but slightly rumpled from having stayed home from school for the last two days, and he carries a small stuffed toy for comfort.\n\nHe is an active second-grade student who enjoys soccer, building with blocks, drawing dinosaurs, and playing simple video games with his older cousin. He lives with his parents and a younger sister in a suburban apartment and attends school regularly, where several classmates have recently had colds. He usually sleeps well, but over the past three nights he has had disrupted sleep because of nasal congestion and nighttime coughing. His appetite is reduced compared with baseline, though he is still drinking fluids and asking for popsicles and soup.\n\n{patientName}'s symptoms began about three days ago with sneezing, sore throat, and clear rhinorrhea, progressing to nasal congestion, low-grade fever, and cough. His mother reports that he has remained playful between symptoms, though he tires a bit faster than usual. There is no respiratory distress, no cyanosis, no drooling, and no inability to tolerate oral intake. He has not complained of ear pain or significant sinus pain. His parents are attentive and supportive, and his grandmother helps with childcare after school.\n\nThe family lifestyle is generally healthy. Meals are home-cooked most days, and screen time is limited on school nights. There is no smoking in the home, though the family has a cat that sleeps in the living room. Immunizations are up to date for age. He has a close group of friends at school and is generally described as cheerful, energetic, and sociable."
          }
        ]
      }
    },
    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:f8ad162b-71cf-468d-8ac8-2a5bfc018011",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
          "status": "generated",
          "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\">patient-history</div>"
        },
        "category": [
          {
            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-history"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} has been previously healthy with normal growth and development and no history of chronic cardiopulmonary disease. He has no known asthma diagnosis, no prior pneumonia, and no history of recurrent sinus or ear infections. He was born at term without major perinatal complications and has had routine pediatric care with vaccinations current for age. He has never been hospitalized overnight.\n\nHis past medical history is notable only for occasional seasonal allergic rhinitis in the spring, usually managed with environmental measures and intermittent antihistamine use. There is no regular prescription medication use. His mother reports no recent travel, no known exposure to tuberculosis, and no exposure to tobacco smoke at home. Several children in his classroom have had recent cough and cold symptoms, making a viral community exposure likely.\n\nOver the current illness, {patientName} has had low-grade fever at home, nasal congestion, sore throat, and nonproductive cough for three days. He has continued to drink fluids with mildly decreased solid food intake and has had normal urine output. There has been no vomiting, diarrhea, rash, neck stiffness, stridor, shortness of breath, or lethargy. His parents brought him in primarily because of persistent congestion, nighttime cough, and concern about fever."
          }
        ]
      }
    }
